cs.DS, cs.CC, cs.GT, cs.AI, cs.CG

Reasoning: The paper deals with the complexity of a zero-player game on switch graphs, which involves graph theory and computational complexity. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also involves complexity classes such as NP, coNP, and PLS, which suggests that it could belong to cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The game theory aspect of the paper could place it in cs.GT (Game Theory). The use of witnesses and termination/non-termination suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the switch graphs used in the paper could place it in cs.CG (Computational Geometry).
